Oct 6 2007 	Awful -- One Star is Too Many	Hotel Union Square is a zero-star establishment. This property is an antiquated dump in an excellent location. Untiil the hotel is renovated, don't waste your time or money.We booked the Hotel Union Square at $189/night because it was recommended in connection with a conference, because it was centrally located, and because the hotel's website presented it as a boutique hotel.The property's Union Square location was excellent, but it is in no way a boutique establishment, despire a renovated lobby and-- as of September 2007-- three (3) renovated guestrooms. Here's our experience for your edification.The first room we were shown (on the fourth floor) was perhaps big enough to swing a cat, but hardly sufficient for two. The furnishings were threadbare (indeed, downright shabby) and the room overlooked the hotel parking lot. But that wasn't the deal breaker. I had work to do on the computer and the (small) desk did not have a free outlet. We requested another room.The second room, a supposed upgrade on the third floor, did indeed have a (small) desk with an outlet. But the room had no windows and no air conditioning, although the temperature outside was in the 80s. The room also possessed an internal airshaft, which allowed the guest to peer into a Dickensian metallic contraption, and was downright creepy.Having struck out with both rooms, we checked out immediately. To its credit, the Hotel Union Square gave us access to its business center to enable us to book another hotel (the excellent Nikko, for a mere $40 additional per night). When I remarked to the desk clerk that the rooms we were shown did not match the advertising on the Hotel Union Square's website, the clerk commented &quot;I wish you would tell our marketing people that. A lot of people come here and are disappointed-- it's not what they expect.&quot;Our young and patient bellman had lugged our baggage from the parking area to the fourth floor, to the third floor, and back to the parking lot. We tipped him for the service that he'd provided, and apologized for our rapid check-out, noting that we were not the type of people who usually checked out of a hotel upon arrival. Said the bellman, &quot; Don't worry, it happens all the time.&quot;Don't let this happen to you, at least not at $189/night. Avoid this dump until the promised renovation is completed, and do find out in advance if your room has air conditioning if you are booking for the warmer months.	
Oct 1 2007 	Sufficient for us	We stayed at Hotel Union Square for 5 nights during the last week of September. The hotel is exactly what I expected. We booked online after I made sure I looked at other people's reviews on Trip Advisor. We ended up paying an average of $226/night which I find pricey for this type of hotel but there was a large convention the same week we were there so the prices were higher elsewhere. It had to suffice considering a 4 to 5 star hotel was well above $400/night. We just needed a clean place to sleep and shower and we got that.It was clean for a boutique hotel but it does show its' age. However, knowing this location is renovating, signs of wear and tear were reasonable.We stayed in room 601 on the top floor facing the main street. Just outside our room door was the ice machine. There was hardly any noise from this common area. No worries at all. This was a non-smoking room, but it does have cigarette stains around the sink, but we couldn't smell smoke at all. The noise wasn't that bad from the streets. We mostly heard the cable cars ringing their bells. We brought earplugs just in case but I didn't have to use them. This particular room had no ceiling fan, no AC and no desk. It did have wireless internet, a small stuffy closet and a reasonably sized bathroom but the toilet kept on running every few minutes. On the first night we filled out a comment card regarding the toilet but no one acknowledged us. We got use to it and just kept the bathroom door closed. The fan didn't work in the bathroom, but that wasn't too big a deal. There is only one elevator but the wait isn't that bad. The hallway to our hotel room always had a funky old smell which I wasn't fond of. The location of this hotel is awesome!!! It's very centrally located. Nearby are: Wallgreens, DSW, Sephora, Blondies Pizza, Tad's Steak House, Bangkok Thai food, H&amp;M, Cable Car, F-Train, Westfield Mall, etc... Everything is within walking distance.	
