Aug 11 2007 	Really pleased	Myself, my partner and antother couple stayed at this hotel on 24th June 2007. We stayed there for 3 nights. We were really pleased with all aspects of our accommodation and would definitely stay here again. After enduring two very long flights we were relieved to have somewhere nice to recuperate. The hotel, especially the rooms, were very clean-bedding, towels changed regularly etc. The rooms were kitted out well in terms of appliances-hair dryer (very important lol), iron, coffee maker etc. The bathroom was very clean and the showers are fab-very powerful. In terms of location the hotel was great. The tram station was directly on our doorstep and it took a single short route to Fisherman's Wharf. The trams cost $5 per person, one way and is something everyone should experience when going to San Fran. The hotel is also very close to the 'F' bus which costs hardly anything at all. This also takes you to Fisherman's Wharf but also makes stops at the various piers. We found this useful when visiting Alkatraz (this is also a fantastic, unmissable trip).The hotel is also a 3 minute walk away from Bloomindales, Maceys and Tiffany's. Also, cycling across the Golden Gate Bridge is a must. Hire your bikes from Fisherman's Whalf and clyle alsong the side of the water to the bridge which usually takes about 45 minutes.At nights we could often here the noise from ouside but this is to be expected from a busy city, it added to the mood and it wasn't enough to keep me awake at night even though i am a very light sleeper.The hotel reception staff were extremely welcoming, polite and helpful. They suggested some lively spots and bars to to go to at nights as well as restaurants. There is a complimentary wine reception ecah day, in the hotel reception, from 6pm.Unfortunately, our stay was just for 3 nights as were were travelling onto Yosemite, Monterery, Santa Barbra, LA and then Vagas. We hoped that the following accommodation would be just as nice.	
Aug 1 2007 	Not So Square Hotel Union Square	My traveling companion and I spent three wonderful nights at the Hotel Union Square. I had reserved a double/double and was pleasantly surprised at check-in to have been upgraded to the Dashiell Hammett Suite. Wow! The style of the entire hotel is so hip. There are little nooks and crannies throughout the hotel adorned with period pieces of furniture and artwork. The hotel is immaculate. Complimentary wine in the evenings and coffee in the morning. The location couldn't be better. Westfield Shopping Centre is two short blocks away. The most impressive aspect of the hotel is the staff. Everyone was friendly and compentent . We were greeted coming and going and always asked if assistance was needed. Honestly, I'm puzzled as to why the hotel doesn't charge more for accommodations. They could certainly get it. Addressing the comments of some of the other posters: San Francisco is a 24-hour city. There is street noise and the usual &quot;inconveniences&quot; that go with crowded environs. I never felt unsafe. I always took a taxi when I wasn't sure of my surroundings. If noise bothers you request an interior room. I learned to take earplugs with me years ago! I recommend this property without hesitation.	
Jul 24 2007	Just Wonderful!!	We last stayed here about 18 years ago! We had a great stay then and were happy to come back due to the hotel's fantastic location one block away from Union Square. Since our first stay the hotel has had a makover (or two possibly,) and the reception area has been completely modernised. I totally echo the comments made by Cibo01 in a previous review regarding decorations - they are so unimportant. We found the staff to be really helpful and pleasant - no problems there at all. If you visit in the Summer I would recommend a room with a ceiling fan overlooking the car park. It's pretty quiet and you can leave the window open for air.I hope it won't be another 18 years before we go back!	
Jul 21 2007 	Great location for the budget conscious	So you've read the mixed reports and yes they are probably all correct. The staff are really friendly and helpful, the location is excellent, the rooms are comfortable, you get lots of goodies but yes the paint work is tired.So if you are worried about how many layers of paint are on the walls, or that you need a modern bathroom then don't stay here. However, we would have no hesitation going back, the rooms are clean the linen and bedding is really comfortable and as long as you ask for a quiet room, we had a really good nights sleep.Its got a really homey feel despite the unusual decor but it is more like staying at your grandparents than in an inner city hotel. We stayed on the 3rd floor and had a ceiling fan, it might have been a hot night if we had not had a ceiling fan so maybe ask for a room with this if visiting in summer.For the money you couldn't ask for a better placed hotel, only a block to Union Square, the cable car to the water stops nearly outside and the turnaround for the cable car is about 100 metres down the road, although the queues are a nightmare during the day.So if you are on a budget but want a good location and a decent night's sleep, look no further!	
Jul 10 2007	A Gem Of A Hotel 	This is my second stay at the Hotel Union Square and both times were delightful. The rooms are very comfortable and come with loads of goodies. The parking is very easy and the staff is always welcoming and helpful. The most surprising thing is how quiet it is and the relaxed feeling you get as soon as you enter the tastefully decorated lobby. Surprising because this little hotel sits right in the heart of San Francisco's shopping district - within easy walking to many stores, great restaurants and entertainment. I look forward to my next stay at Hotel Union Square.	
Jul 8 2007 	Lots of compromise for great location	Our travel agency in Brussels booked us into this hotel and was too late to change. After listening to the advice of other members, we decided to ask for the room facing the courtyard on the upper floor. The room we were given was on the top floor (6th floor) Room no. 622 (?) standard room with double bed . It is very small and the bathroom is very old fashion and dim. The bed is small but comfortable. There is no net curtain and if you open the curtain, people in the opposite room or in the hallway can see directly into your room. If you draw the curtain, it is dark as the curtain is rather thick. There is no air conditioned but fortunately in late June it is not too hot. Location is excellent and staff are friendly. However the concierge double as bell boy is very snotty. I passed by a twin room on the same floor - it is big and rather nice.	
Jun 23 2007 	Avoid it no matter how centrally located it is !	We’ve stayed at the hotel for the first days of our trip across California and the Southwest. While our travel agent and the website of the hotel gave us some confidence, that the place is not a tourist trap, we found it one of the most &quot;fishy&quot; places we have stayed at throughout our trip: A dark room, where you could not fall on the floor as the walls have been narrow enough to keep you up, a bathroom my grandparents might have seen in their parents’ home, a window towards the &quot;courtyard&quot; which gives you the feeling of staying in a prison cell and paper-thin walls, allowing us to follow most of the activities of our neighbors next room. Staff at check in and out is friendly and the location nearby Union Square is good, but we are sure, there are a couple of other hotels in this area with better rooms and amenities.	
Jun 13 2007 	Nice place to stay overall.	Okay, if you have read the other reviews then you probably don't know what to make of this place. It's not the typical American hotel with huge rooms and massive beds. Its got character and it's not a new building so yes it can have a few quirks such as musty smells and a bit of faded paintwork. But hey, it's not the end of the world is it?The hotel staff were very friendly and always cheerful in our experience. There is complimentary tea and coffee every morning AND wine in the evenings. Just get their early because the other people staying there with us were very thirsty! Also a nice bag of free toiletries in the bathroom and a gift card for the jewellers next door (use it and see what you get)Our room was facing the street so we got woken up a few times by the seemingly very busy SFFD and the bin men but again, stay in the city, expect city noises! The other bonus was that it was fairly cheap to stay there. It's well placed for getting around town as the cable car goes right past the front door down to Fishermans Wharf.We would stay there again but might ask for a room away from the street!!	
